%I A275939 #58 Jun 17 2026 19:15:38
%S A275939 608981813029,26861,11,608981813017,71,192252423729713,37,11,23
%N A275939 Consider the prime race mod n (where n >= 2) between n*k+1 and n*k-1. Terms are numbers n*k+1 where n*k+1 first takes lead over n*k-1.
%C A275939 Values are available for all 2 <= n <= 999 except for 12 and 24. If n is odd and > 3 then 2*n will have the same value in the sequence as n.
%C A275939 Additional terms starting with n = 12 are:
%C A275939 unknown, 53, 71, 331, 17, 239, 37, 213827, 1381, 673, 23, 47, unknown, 101, 53, 379, 29, 59, 331
%C A275939 The longest n*k+1 versus n*k-1 races up to n = 999 are for n = 3,6,8,12,24 and 168. When n = 168 the race ends at prime 273084304417.
%C A275939 The mod 12 and 24 races were checked by computer to 1.1 * 10^14 without n*k+1 ever leading.
%C A275939 Kevin Ford (private communication) provides the following information on these races: "My paper with Richard Hudson contains a lot of information about the location of sign changes for pi(x,q,a)-pi(x,q,b). Corollary 4 has rigorous upper bounds, but these will likely not be useful to you. The information in Tables 2 and 3 will be more helpful, as these provide the most likely places to look for the first sign change. In the case of the mod 12 race, it is probably around exp(187.536), or about 2.79 x 10^{81}. For the mod 24 race, it's about exp(43.453)=7.437... x 10^{18}".
%C A275939 In line with Ford and Hudson's prediction, for n=24, residue 1 leads -1 at 7390188907282602529; for n=12, residue 1 does not lead -1 up to 10^19. - _Benjamin Chaffin_, Jun 11 2026
%D A275939 Ford, Kevin; Konyagin, Sergei; Chebyshev's conjecture and the prime number race. IV International Conference "Modern Problems of Number Theory and its Applications": Current Problems, Part II (Russian) (Tula, 2001), 67-91.
%D A275939 Paulo Ribenboim, The Little Book of Big Primes, Springer 1991
%H A275939 Kevin Ford and Richard H. Hudson, <a href="https://www.impan.pl/en/publishing-house/journals-and-series/acta-arithmetica/all/en/publishing-house/journals-and-series/acta-arithmetica/all/100/4/82565/sign-changes-in-pi-q-a-x-pi-q-b-x">Sign changes in pi q,a(x) - pi q,b(x)</a>, Acta Arithmetica 100 (2001), 297-314.
%H A275939 Kevin Ford and Sergei Konyagin, <a href="https://arxiv.org/abs/1910.08983">Chebyshev's conjecture and the prime number race</a>, arXiv:1910.08983 [math.NT], 2019.
%H A275939 Andrew Granville and Greg Martin, <a href="http://www.dms.umontreal.ca/~andrew/PDF/PrimeRace.pdf">Prime Number Races</a>, Amer. Math. Monthly, 113 (No. 1, 2006), 1-33.
%H A275939 Andy Martin, <a href="/A275939/a275939.txt">Values for 2 to 999 as far as they are known</a>
%H A275939 Andy Martin, <a href="/A275939/a275939.c.txt">C program</a>
%e A275939 For n=5, the mod 5 values of the primes 2,3,5 and 7 are 2,3,0 and 2 respectively, so there is no change in the race. For the next prime 11, mod 5 gives 1, n*k+1 now leads 1 to 0, and the race is over.
